content.text: When an order is placed for a customer with an agreement that does not specify discounts for specific products, IFS applies the discount to the products again after the order is placed (discounts are included already in the pricing displayed on the storefront/used for order placement).
There are about a dozen customers who have agreements in place like this.
This issue does not currently happen for customers who have agreements that have specific product discounts.

We confirmed on the 1/10 call that the website is passing in the correct saleUnitPrice (the discounted product price) in these cases. Since it seems like IFS is doing the additional discounting without any influence from the website/order submission process, we think it might be helpful if you were able to reach out to your IFS/ERP implementation partner to bounce this off of them and see if they have any ideas. We'd also be happy to collaborate or jump on a call if that would be helpful.
Otherwise, if there isn't a reasonable solution from the ERP side of things, we would recommend the following steps:

Use Postman (or another web client tool) to submit an order to the Test IFS instance for a customer with this type of agreement set up. This order would be submitted with non-discounted pricing to verify that IFS applies the discount after the order is placed.

If this works, a potential solution could be to flag each of the customers that have this type of agreement (either manually or via the customer refresh job) and then use different pricing logic for the flagged customers so that IFS receives and processes their orders differently (and wouldn't apply the double discount). This may also be reliant on what pricing data IFS is able to provide us via the real-time calls.
This would be with the understanding that the pricing reflected on the storefront always needs to be respective of the agreement/discounts in place.
